My Review: This book is so simply written that I was able to fly through it in just a few days. I most likely wouldn't have picked it up if I had read what it was about, so would recommend starting there if you can.

Title: Red Rising (Red Rising Saga, #1)
Author: Pierce Brown
My Review:
The final chapters were quick page turners and I was interested to see how it ended, but not the series for me.

Almost every challenge Darrow faces is immediately solved a couple paragraphs later (Ambushed by a genetically modified bear that was designed to kill him? Just jump over here and the bear falls through a trapdoor to its death.). It started to feel lazy to the point that you never really believe he is in any danger at all.

Title: The Diary of a Young Girl
Author: Anne Frank
Additional Authors: Otto H. Frank, Mirjam Pressler, Susan Massotty, Eleanor Roosevelt
My Review:
This book was not what I expected. I expected the entries to mostly be about the war, but was surprised to see how much of it felt like a, for the lack of a better word, normal teenager's diary—from annoyance with parents to general hopes for her future as an adult.

It was inspiring to see the positive attitude she held onto given the circumstances. I'd have crumbled under far easier circumstances.

Author: Jeanette Winterson

Title: Hell of a Book
Author: Jason Mott
My Review: This book felt like a nice fictional wrapper around Between the World and Me. I really enjoyed the narration from a character you can't 100% trust and imagining the reactions from the other people in the scene.

Title: How to Talk So Kids Will Listen & Listen So Kids Will Talk
Author: Adele Faber
My Review:
Perhaps this books was helpful when it was originally published, but I don't think it's aged well. I learned most of these lessons from more contemporary books or parenting Instagram accounts (thanks @biglittlefeelings). A lot of it feels obvious and boils down to treating your kid with respect. It makes me happy that parenting has progressed in a way that makes this book feel unnecessary...potentially because of the impact that books like this had decades ago. So thanks for that.

I would recommend reading this book if you want to read cringy examples of clearly fake dialog that the author suggests actually happened.

Title: A Memory Called Empire (Teixcalaan, #1)
Author: Arkady Martine
My Review:
This felt like a political drama that happened to be in space. That's not necessarily a bad thing, but in this instance I found myself wanting more from the world around the characters. Maybe the subsequent books get into that more, but I'm not sure I'll ever make it to those.

There were definitely enjoyable characters and moments in the book, but overall I was just trying to get through it.

Title: A Gentleman in Moscow
Author: Amor Towles
My Review: One of the most enjoyable books I've read in recent memory. Full of perfectly executed humor and great characters.

Author: William Deresiewicz

Title: I Who Have Never Known Men
Author: Jacqueline Harpman

Title: Tenth of December
Author: George Saunders
My Review: It was fun to read short stories by George Saunders after reading A Swim in a Pond in the Rain by him last year. Some of the stories felt masterful and made me rethink my expectations of the genre. Maybe a short story can be as full and satisfying as a novel.

Title: Remarkably Bright Creatures
Author: Shelby Van Pelt
My Review: I really wasn't captured by any of the characters in this book. Even the octopus fell short of what I was hoping for (and the octopus was the reason I chose to read the book). Cameron in particular was cartoonishly rude to everyone, especially the people who helped him, while continuing to shout about how smart he is.

Title: Good Inside: A Practical Guide to Resilient Parenting Prioritizing Connection Over Correction
Author: Becky   Kennedy

Title: SPQR: A History of Ancient Rome
Author: Mary Beard

Title: Meditations
Author: Marcus Aurelius
My Review:
I read Cloud Cuckoo Land earlier this year and it gave me a new appreciation for text that has lasted thousands of years. What an amazing opportunity to see into the mind of a Roman emperor 2000 years ago. If more world leaders (or people in general) had the internal dialog that Marcus has, we would be living in less selfish times.

This is a book that probably warrants revisiting from time to time. There were days when I just wanted to get through a few passages without really reflecting on what he was writing. It probably would have been better to read a single passage and sit with it for a day.

This was one of the first mindfulness books that I felt slipping into parts of my daily life. I am far from being someone I would describe as a mindful person, but it felt like I got a little closer while reading this.

I may never wash dishes the same way again.

Title: The Passenger (The Passenger #1)
Author: Cormac McCarthy
My Review:
I was really excited when I heard that there would be 2 new Cormac McCarthy books this year. The Road still stands as one of my favorite books of all time.

However, I was disappointed with this book (though not disappointed enough to skip book #2). I never felt fully engaged with the story or the main character. There were the moments of beautifully simple passages that McCarthy is capable of, but the story as a whole felt a little hollow. I still have hope for book #2 to be great.

Title: The Winners (Beartown, #3)
Author: Fredrik Backman
My Review: I'm a big fan of this series and the latest addition does not disappoint. A lot of the same characters dealing with a lot of the same struggles. At times it felt like there were too many storylines, which led to some of them being underdeveloped. I've grown so attached to some of the characters I felt like there were whole worlds within them that could still be explored. Maybe for another book?

Title: Unlikely Animals
Author: Annie  Hartnett
My Review:
Ever since I became a parent I've really enjoyed books that focus on familial relationships. This book made me think about what you owe the people in your family. It's often a question that we save until there's a pending deadline.

I also appreciated how this book handled death, not living up to your potential, and addiction with humor.

Oh, and ghosts. Gave me fond memories of the ghosts from Lincoln in the Bardo.
